<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-755-330  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 755 330.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  July 1990 v9 n7 p100(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software delivers on documentation. (includes related articles onCALS and curbing documentation chaos)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Beckert, Beverly A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Technical documentation requires more powerful computing solutionsthan those provided by desktop publishing.andP;  Technical documentsare usually long, usually several hundred pages, and have anextended shelf life.andP;  They are made up of text and graphicelements and usually have a very structured format; color israrely used.andP;  The manuals are usually created by a group ofwriters and illustrators; these people may use different types ofcomputers.andP;  Technical documents are usually produced onworkstations that are hooked together by a local area network sodata can be shared.andP;  Electronic technical publishing integratesthe three basic activities that go into producing a technicaldocument: word processing, graphics, and layout.andP;  The federalgovernment's Computer Aided Logistics Support (CALS) sets up theuse of specific standards for electronic interchange of documentsand support information between contractors and governmentagencies; many publishing vendors are planning to support CALS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     DocumentationDocument PreparationNational GovernmentWorkstationsTechnical Writing.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   For more information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>